{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HboPWjojEAo9fqixVuQkj3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The original test was **already broken** — the error is `PlatformConfig account not found`. This is a pre-existing issue: the settlement code can't find the PlatformConfig account in the mock connection because the config account PDA is set up in `beforeEach` only for the `app` mock connection, but when `db = createDb(DATABASE_URL, rawSql)` is used, the `withTransaction` on the rawSql breaks the settlement transaction.\n\nWait — looking at the log: `PlatformConfig account not found at 4hYti4gGomEfpT8gAHhHvmvENshCMndyG9Qokj993yDU`. The mock connection has the config account set up, but it seems to use a different PDA. Let me check...\n\nActually, the real problem is the `createDb(DATABASE_URL, rawSql)` approach makes `withTransaction` use `rawSql.begin()` which works, but inside the transaction, the `settleMatch` function reads the PlatformConfig account from the connection. The settlement flow:\n1. Poll finds locked match\n2. `settleMatch()` reads config from connection → works\n3. `settleMatch()` calls `db.withTransaction()` → this calls `rawSql.begin(txSql => ...)` \n\nBut actually, the error says `PlatformConfig account not found`. The settle code reads the config PDA. It's using `COINFLIP_PROGRAM_ID` to derive the PDA. Let me check if the issue is that the original test was already broken by the `withTransaction` change, or by the `_txSql` approach.\n\nLet me look at the settle-tx code to see exactly when config is read:"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":898,"cache_read_input_tokens":90802,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":898},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"773e2b1e-9c3d-4d53-809d-a95c